To create a cone with a flat tip bottom, we'll essentially create two cones and position them to form a frustum (the shape of a cone with the top cut off). Here's how you can modify the `draw()` function in the `sketch.js` file:

```javascript
function draw() {
  let cupHeight = 100;
  let cupWidth = 50;
  let cylinderHeight = cupHeight / 4;
  let cylinderWidth = cupWidth * 3;
  let flatTipHeight = 10; // Control the height of the flat tip

  background(200);
  ambientLight(100);
  pointLight(255, 255, 255, mouseX - width / 2, mouseY - height / 2, 200);

  rotateX(frameCount * 0.01);
  rotateY(frameCount * 0.01);

  // Draw cylinder
  push();
  fill(150, 0, 0);
  translate(0, (cylinderHeight + (cupHeight - flatTipHeight)) / 2, 0);
  cylinder(cylinderWidth, cylinderHeight);
  pop();

  // Draw top cone
  push();
  fill(0, 0, 150);
  translate(0, -(cupHeight - flatTipHeight) / 2, 0);
  rotateX(PI);
  cone(cupWidth, cupHeight - flatTipHeight); // Reduce cone height by flatTipHeight
  pop();

  // Draw bottom cone (flat tip)
  push();
  fill(0, 0, 150);
  translate(0, flatTipHeight, 0);
  rotateX(PI);
  cone(cupWidth - (flatTipHeight * 2), flatTipHeight * 2); // Make bottom cone smaller
  pop();
}
```

You can adjust the `flatTipHeight` variable to control the height of the flat tip at the bottom of the cone. In this example, I've set it to 10 units.

Creating a custom 3D model for a shape with a round, bowl-shaped bottom and a cylindrical, straight side can be done through a combination of two 3D primitives in p5.js: `sphere()` and `cylinder()`. Here is an example of how you can achieve this:

First, make sure to include the p5.js library and the p5.js webGL library in your HTML file:

